[Carbon monoxide (CO) is a deadly odorless and colorless gas. CO is most often associated with the fumes from burning fuel in some type of engine, a car, a small engine, a boiler, a gas furnace, or a grill. CO can build up, particularly indoors, and be the source of a poisoning of multiple people.

In lower doses, a person may experience headaches or dizziness or faint. But in other instances, the high level can overcome a person with little or no warning. Furthermore, those with heart or lung disease may be at more risk of collapsing.

Generally, if provided fresh breathing air in a timely manner, the affected individual can recover. However, it does not take a long time of breathing high levels of CO to result in death.

We hope the affected individuals taken to the hospital have fully recovered. Likely the hotel is closed until the air handling system is repaired. Perhaps carbon monoxide detectors should be checked as frequently as fire or smoke alarms. This article clearly indicates that such a detector was a life saver in this incident. - Mod.TG

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Manitoba, Canada: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6564012,278]
